
@startuml

class User {
  +id: String (unique)
  +name: String
  +email: String
  +dateOfBirth: Date
  -account: Account
}

class Account {
  +accountNumber: String (unique)
  +type: String ("personal" | "business")
  -user: User
  -pages: Set<Page>
}

class Page {
  +name: String (unique per account)
  +visitCount: Integer
  -account: Account
  -type: String ("normal" | "advertisement")
  -adPageFeatures: Map<String, Double> (if type is advertisement)
}

class AdvertisementPage {
  +bounceRate: Double
  +clickThroughRate: Double
  +conversionRate: Double
  -page: Page
}

User "1" -- "1" Account : has
Account "1" -- "0..*" Page : manages
Page "1" -- "1" Account : belongs to
Page "1" -- "1" AdvertisementPage : is a type of (if applicable)

@enduml

---

### ✅ Explanation:

- **User**: Represents a user who signs up with personal details. Each user has exactly one `Account`.
- **Account**: Can be either a `personal` or `business` type. It is uniquely identified by an `accountNumber`. Each `Account` can manage multiple `Pages`.
- **Page**: A page created by an account. Each page must have a unique name within the same account. Pages can be of type `normal` or `advertisement`.
- **AdvertisementPage**: A special type of `Page` that includes metrics like bounce rate, click-through rate, and conversion rate.

---

### 📌 Notes:
- The relationship between `User` and `Account` is **one-to-one**.
- The relationship between `Account` and `Page` is **one-to-many**.
- The `Page` class has a **composition** relationship with `AdvertisementPage` (only if it's an ad page).
- The `name` attribute in `Page` is **unique per account**, not globally.

